    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-03-04T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-03-04T00:00:00-05:00" n="1037"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1037">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811B.011/10</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Under Secretary of State</hi> (<hi
                        rend="italic">Phillips</hi>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-03-04">March 4,
                            1935</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>When the Japanese Ambassador was here this afternoon he handed me the
                    accompanying paper,<note n="70" xml:id="d1037fn70">
                        <hi rend="italic">Infra</hi>.</note> which he said should not strictly have
                    been called “memorandum”, relating to Article 13, Sections 13 and 16 of the
                    Draft Constitution of the Philippines,<note n="71" xml:id="d1037fn71">See
                        Article XII, secs. 1 and 5, <hi rend="italic">Constitution of the
                            Philippines Adopted by the Philippine Constitutional Convention at the
                            City of Manila, Philippine Islands, on the 8th Day of February
                        1935</hi>, Senate Document No. 43, 74th Cong., 1st sess. (Washington,
                        Government Printing Office, 1935).</note> which contains certain provisions
                    restricting the right of foreign nationals to develop and <pb facs="1193"
                        n="1081" xml:id="pg_1081"/> exploit natural resources in the Philippines. He
                    said he realized it was a delicate matter for him to take up with us, but his
                    Government felt that such a provision should, if possible, be deleted from the
                    Constitution, but failing in this he asked whether there could not be a clause
                    added to the Constitution granting rights to foreign nationals on the basis of
                    reciprocity; the last paragraph of his so-called “memorandum” discusses this
                    point.</p>
                <p>I said that I would give the matter consideration, but could not undertake to
                    express any opinion at the present time.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">William Phillips</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
